<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900621-0040</DOCNO><DOCID>900621-0040.</DOCID><HL>   Credit Rating:   General Dynamics'   Debt Rating Is Cut   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>06/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   GD</CO><IN>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)</IN><LP>   Moody's Investors Service Inc. said it downgraded about$670 million of General Dynamics Corp. debt, citing aslowdown in military spending and potentially major costoverruns on a Navy aircraft contract.   The downgrades are part of a continuing appraisal ofaerospace and defense contractors by Moody's. &quot;The prospectsfor cuts in the defense budget have triggered our concern forthe industry as a whole and this company in particular,&quot; saidTassos Philipakkos, Moody vice president and aerospaceanalyst.</LP><TEXT>   Moody's said it downgraded General Dynamics' senior debtto Baa-1 from A-2. The company's subordinated debt waslowered to Baa-2 from A-3, and its commercial paper was cutto Prime-2 from Prime-1. Ratings on the company's GeneralDynamics Credit Corp. unit also were lowered by like amounts.   Moody's announcement was made shortly before the end oftrading. General Dynamics stock closed at $34.50, off 62.5cents, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.   The reductions for senior and subordinated debt are by twonotches, a sharper cut than the one-notch reductions thatMoody's made recently on McDonnell Douglas Corp. and GrummanCorp. securities. General Dynamics and McDonnell Douglas arebased in St. Louis. Grumman is based in Bethpage, N.Y. Mr.Philipakkos said that both of General Dynamics' competitorshad been more recently downgraded, while General Dynamics hadremained at its peak rating.   Moody's said General Dynamics is heavily dependent onmilitary contracts, citing particularly expected productioncuts for the Army's M-1 tank and the Air Force's F-16fighter.</TEXT></DOC>